    "analysis": "The previous step filtered trace series within the failure window and identified multiple trace-level anomalies. Key observations from that result: \n- Earliest trace anomalies appear at ~2021-03-07 07:31:00+08 (e.g., IG01.trace.to_Tomcat01.duration_mean and MG01.trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95). Additional trace spikes occur at ~07:33 (IG02.trace.self.duration_p95) and later (07:39+). \n- Trace anomalies show relatively high severities for MG01-related traces (MG01.trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 severity ~4.4 at 07:31; MG01.trace.from_dockerB2.duration_p95 severity ~3.5 at 07:33). IG01 trace.self.duration_mean and trace.to_Tomcat01 anomalies start at ~07:31 as well (severity ~1.2–1.4). \n- Error logs from apache01/apache02 cluster around ~07:36:21+08 and log.error_count spikes for apache at ~07:36, which is later than the earliest trace anomalies. \nInterpretation so far: a latency slowdown starts in traces around 07:31 (notably MG01 and IG01/IG02 traces), followed by frontend apache errors at ~07:36. This suggests a downstream service slowdown (likely MG01 or IG01/IG02 call chains) that propagated to frontend causing errors. To pinpoint the root cause component and exact occurrence time we must inspect raw trace anomaly rows (timestamps, trace names and values) in chronological order to 1) identify the absolute first sustained anomalous trace point and 2) determine which downstream service in call chains was faulty. The next step is therefore to list the raw trace anomaly rows (chronologically) with a simple classification of trace direction (to/from/self) to expose the earliest downstream fault and its timestamp.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Return the raw trace anomaly rows (stored in kernel variable trace_anomaly_rows) sorted by timestamp ascending, limited to the first 50 rows. For each row include columns: timestamp, _dt, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, p95, and add a derived column named 'direction' with value 'to' if trace_name contains 'to_', 'from' if contains 'from_', and 'self' if contains 'self'. Store the displayed table in kernel variable trace_anomaly_rows_display. Keep output compact (max 50 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have identified trace-level anomalies starting earliest at 2021-03-07 07:31:00+08. At that time multiple trace series from IG01, IG02, and MG01 breached their global P95 thresholds (examples: IG01.trace.to_Tomcat01.* and MG01.trace.from_Tomcat01.* and MG01.trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95). MG01-related traces show the largest relative severity (e.g., severity ~4.4 for trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 at 07:31), while IG01/IG02 trace anomalies also appear at ~07:31–07:33. Apache frontend errors appear later (~07:36), suggesting propagation from earlier trace slowdowns. To localize root cause we must inspect the absolute earliest anomalous trace rows (timestamp 07:31) to see which specific call directions and target services were first affected and whether the earliest faulty trace points implicate a particular downstream service (e.g., MG01 vs IG01/IG02). This will tell us which component experienced the first sustained fault and its occurrence time. No final root cause declared yet.",
