{
    "analysis": "The Executor returned the earliest trace anomaly rows at 2021-03-07 07:31:00+08. At that timestamp multiple trace series breached their global P95 simultaneously: IG01 -> to Tomcat01 (duration_mean & duration_p95), IG02 -> to Tomcat04 (duration_mean & duration_p95), and MG01 <- from Tomcat01/dockerA1/dockerB1 (duration_mean, duration_p95, row_count). MG01-related trace series show the largest relative severities in earlier aggregated results (e.g., trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 severity ~4.4). Apache frontend errors and log.error_count spikes were observed later (~07:36), so the temporal ordering is: trace slowdowns begin at ~07:31 (MG01, IG01, IG02 implicated) -> later frontend errors at ~07:36. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must now perform metric analysis (on components implicated by traces) to identify faults (consecutive anomalous KPI subsequences) and determine which component and KPI first experienced a sustained fault. This will let us decide the root cause component and exact occurrence time. No final root cause declared yet.",
  "completed": "False",
  "instruction": "Within the window 2021-03-07 07:30:00+08 to 2021-03-07 08:00:00+08, focus metric analysis on components MG01, IG01, and IG02. Using the precomputed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name):\n1) Produce an aggregated table for these three components with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value>p95 or value>0 if p95==0), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, p95, max_value_in_window, severity = max_value_in_window / max(p95,1e-9). Limit to rows with anomaly_count>0 and return top 20 ordered by anomaly_count desc then severity desc.\n2) From that aggregated table select the top 5 (by anomaly_count then severity). For each of these top 5 (component,kpi) pairs return the raw anomaly rows within the window sorted by timestamp ascending, with columns: timestamp, _dt, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, p95. Limit these raw rows to at most 50 rows per KPI (but overall display compactly).\nStore the aggregated table in kernel variable metric_candidate_agg and the concatenated raw anomaly rows in metric_candidate_rows for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric analysis for the candidate components (MG01, IG01, IG02) found anomalies only on IG01 KPIs (several CPU metrics and JVM heap used). However those IG01 metric anomalies occur later in the window (examples: CPUWio around 07:40, JVM heap used at ~07:50). Trace analysis showed earliest anomalies at 2021-03-07 07:31:00+08 where multiple trace series breached thresholds: IG01 -> to Tomcat01, IG02 -> to Tomcat04, and MG01 <- from Tomcat01/dockerA1/dockerB1. MG01-related trace series had the largest relative severity (e.g., MG01.trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 severity ~4.4 at 07:31). Apache frontend error logs cluster later at ~07:36. The temporal ordering is: trace slowdowns start ~07:31 (MG01, IG01, IG02 implicated) -> frontend apache errors at ~07:36 -> IG01 metric anomalies later (~07:40+). This suggests the initial fault likely originated in a service identified by traces (MG01 or IG01/IG02) at ~07:31 rather than IG01 metric KPIs (which show later resource pressure). To decide the root cause component we need to determine which implicated downstream service(s) were the first and most severely affected in traces. The next step is to aggregate trace anomalies by implicated target service (extracted from trace_name) and report, per target, the anomaly count, earliest anomaly timestamp, maximum severity (value/p95), and which cmdb_id(s) observed those anomalies. This will help identify the most likely downstream faulty component and the exact occurrence time. No final root cause declared yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full trace anomaly rows stored in kernel variable trace_anomaly_rows, aggregate anomalies by the implicated target (the 'implicated' column). For each implicated target compute: implicated (target name), anomaly_row_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min _dt), latest_anomaly_timestamp (max _dt), distinct_cmdb_ids_list (which cmdb_id(s) reported anomalies referencing this target), and max_severity where severity = value / max(p95,1e-9). Return a compact table limited to the top 20 implicated targets ordered by anomaly_row_count desc then max_severity desc. Store the returned table in kernel variable trace_implicated_agg and also store the full aggregated DataFrame in kernel for later steps." 
}

